  dummyurl =	 "https://research-information.bris.ac.uk/en/publications/of-flying-frogs-and-levitrons",
  annote =	 "Diamagnetic objects are repelled by magnetic fields. If the
                  fields are strong enough, this repulsion can balance
                  gravity, and objects levitated in this way can be held in
                  stable equilibrium, apparently violating Earnshaw's
                  theorem. In fact Earnshaw's theorem does not apply to
                  induced magnetism, and it is possible for the total energy
                  (gravitational $+$ magnetic) to possess a minimum. General
                  stability conditions are derived, and it is shown that
                  stable zones always exist on the axis of a field with
                  rotational symmetry, and include the inflection point of the
                  magnitude of the field. For the field inside a solenoid, the
                  zone is calculated in detail; if the solenoid is long, the
